   {a + 2{{(x - 1)}^2},} &amp; {for} &amp; {1 &lt; x &lt; 2}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>What is the value of a for which f(x) is continuous at x = $$-$$1 and x = 1?

Consider the following functions<br><br>1. $$f(x) = \left\{ \matrix{
  {1 \over x},\,if\,x \ne 0 \hfill \cr 
  0,\,if\,x = 0 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$<br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {2x + 5,} &amp; {if\,x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {{x^2} + 2x + 5,} &amp; {if\,x \le 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>Which of the above functions is/are derivable at x = 0 ?

explanation:
1. Consider, $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} {{f(0 + h) - f(0)} \over h}$$<br><br>$$ = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} {{1/h - 0} \over h}$$<br><br>$$ = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} {1 \over {{h^2}}} = \infty $$ (not defined)<br><br>Hence, f is not differentiable at x = 0.<br><br>2. We have, $$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {2x + 5,} &amp; {x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {{x^2} + 2x + 5,} &amp; {x \le 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow f'(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {2,} &amp; {x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {2x + 2,} &amp; {x \le 0}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$\because$$ LHL of f'(x) = RHL of f'(x) at x = 0<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f is differentiable at x = 0.

