Consider the following in respect of the function <br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ \matrix{
  2 + x,x \ge 0 \hfill \cr 
  2 - x,x &lt; 0 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$.<br><br>I. $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to 1} f(x)$$ does not exist.<br><br>II. f(x) is differentiable at x = 0.<br><br>III. f(x) is continuous at x = 0.<br><br>Which of the above statements is/are correct?

explanation:
Given, $$f(x) = \left\{ \matrix{
  2 + x,x \ge 0 \hfill \cr 
  2 - x,x &lt; 0 \hfill \cr}  \right.$$<br><br><img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1cpxny0/e5e7191c-2374-43bd-af91-f12d6dbc7897/a98e8f80-afb0-11ec-bcf2-e50bd55ad029/file-1l1cpxny1.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1cpxny0/e5e7191c-2374-43bd-af91-f12d6dbc7897/a98e8f80-afb0-11ec-bcf2-e50bd55ad029/file-1l1cpxny1.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh" alt="NDA 2016 Paper 2 Mathematics - Limit, Continuity and Differentiability Question 56 English Explanation"><br>At x = 1, LHL = $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to {1^ - }} (2 + x) = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} (2 + (1 - h)) = 3$$<br><br>RHL $$ = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to {1^ + }} (2 + x) = \mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} (2 + (1 + h)) = 3$$<br><br>Here, LHL = RHL<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to 1} $$ f(x) exists.<br><br>At x = 0, graph of f(x) makes sharp edge.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is not differentiable at x = 0.<br><br>At x = 0<br><br>LHL = $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to {0^ - }} (2 - x)$$<br><br>= $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} [2 - (0 - h)] = 2$$<br><br>RHL = $$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{x \to {0^ + }} (2 + x)$$<br><br>$$\mathop {\lim }\limits_{h \to 0} [2 + (0 + h)] = 2$$<br><br>Value of f(x) at x = 0<br><br>i.e. f(0) = 2 + 0 = 2<br><br>Here, LHL = RHL = f(x)<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is continuous at x = 0.

We have,<br><br>f : A $$\to$$ R,<br><br>where A = R \ {0}<br><br>such that, $$f(x) = {{x + |x|} \over x}$$<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ $$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {2,} &amp; {x &gt; 0}  \cr 
   {0,} &amp; {x &lt; 0}  \cr 

 } } \right\}$$<br><br>Since, f(x) is not defined for x = 0.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ f(x) is discontinuous at x = 0.<br><br>Also, f(x) is constant function on R $$-$$ {0}.<br><br>Hence, f(x) is continuous on A, where A = R $$-$$ {0}.

We have, <br><br>$$f(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
