 } } \right.$$ ..... (i)<br><br>and $$|f(x)| = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {| - 2|,} &amp; { - 3 \le x \le 0}  \cr 
   {|x - 2|,} &amp; {0 &lt; x \le 3}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow |f(x)| = \left\{ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; { - 3 \le x \le 0}  \cr 
   {(2 - x),} &amp; {2 &lt; x \le 3}  \cr 
   {(x - 2),} &amp; {2 \le x \le 3}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$ ..... (ii)<br><br><img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1cq2o6j/805c9ed2-9450-4837-b78d-89a0146e0874/34c91bb0-afb1-11ec-bcf2-e50bd55ad029/file-1l1cq2o6k.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1cq2o6j/805c9ed2-9450-4837-b78d-89a0146e0874/34c91bb0-afb1-11ec-bcf2-e50bd55ad029/file-1l1cq2o6k.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh" alt="NDA 2016 Paper 2 Mathematics - Limit, Continuity and Differentiability Question 87 English Explanation"><br>From Eqs. (i) and (ii), we get<br><br>$$g(x) = f(|x|) + |f(x)|$$<br><br>$$g(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   { - x} &amp; { - 3 \le x \le 0}  \cr 
   {0,} &amp; {0 &lt; x &lt; 2}  \cr 
   {2x - 4} &amp; {2 \le x \le 3}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>$$g'(x) = \left\{ {\matrix{
   { - 1} &amp; { - 3 \le x \le 0}  \cr 
   {0,} &amp; {0 &lt; x &lt; 2}  \cr 
   2 &amp; {2 \le x \le 3}  \cr 

 } } \right.$$<br><br>The graph of g(x) is given.<br><br>Since, g(x) has sharp edges t x = 0 and x = 2.<br><br>Hence, g(x) is not differentiable at x = 0 and x = 2.

